⚙️ Handling Single File Upload
Example:
const multer = require('multer');
const upload = multer({ dest: 'uploads/' });

app.post('/upload', upload.single('avatar'), (req, res) => {
  console.log(req.file);   // file info
  console.log(req.body);   // text fields
  res.send('File uploaded');
});

👉 Key points:

upload.single('avatar')
File stored in uploads/
Access via req.file

🖼️ Handling Multiple File Uploads
Example:
app.post('/photos', upload.array('photos', 5), (req, res) => {
  console.log(req.files); // array of files
  res.send('Files uploaded');
});
👉 Key points:
upload.array(fieldName, maxCount)
Files available in req.files


⚙️ Storage Configuration Basics

Default storage is simple, but you can customize it.
Disk Storage Example:
const storage = multer.diskStorage({
  destination: (req, file, cb) => {
    cb(null, 'uploads/');
  },
  filename: (req, file, cb) => {
    cb(null, Date.now() + '-' + file.originalname);
  }
});
const upload = multer({ storage });

👉 What you control:
destination → where files go
filename → how files are named



Cloud Storage (Recommended for Production)

Instead of saving locally:

Use services like:
AWS S3
Cloudinary
Firebase Storage

👉 Flow:

Multer (memory storage)
        ↓
Buffer received
        ↓
Upload to cloud API
        ↓
Get file URL
        ↓
Store URL in DB



Serving Uploaded Files
Option 1: Static Folder (Local)
app.use('/uploads', express.static('uploads'));

Access file:

http://localhost:3000/uploads/file.jpg
Option 2: Cloud URL

If using cloud:

You directly return URL like:
https://cdn.example.com/image.jpg

